<p>The conduct of Cortez, when he first landed on the coast of
Mexico, was as remarkable for that hardy spirit of adventure,
to which success gives the name of policy, as his subsequent
operations were for cruelty and perfidy. As soon as his army
was on shore, he dismantled his fleet of such articles as would
be useful in building a new one; he then set fire to his ships
and burnt them in presence of his men, that they might fight
their battles with more desperate courage, knowing that it
would be impossible to save themselves from a victorious enemy
by flight. He constructed a fort, in which the iron and the
rigging were preserved.</p></note> suffocates the skies.</l>
