<attbytes>18Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z100140162</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>An Elegy [1782]</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd1>
<pb n="4">
<dedicat r="italic">
<caption r="smcap"><hi r="roman">TO</hi> Mrs. <hi r="roman">LYDIA HOSMER</hi>, Relict of the late Honorable <hi r="roman">TITUS HOSMER</hi>, Esq; <hi r="roman">THIS ELEGY IS INSCRIBED,</hi></caption>
<hi r="smcapit">As</hi> a Testimony of the Author's
Veneration for the many amiable
Virtues which rendered her the
Delight and Ornament of so worthy a
Consort, and still render her an
Honor to a very numerous and respectable
Acquaintance.</dedicat>
<pb n="5">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140163</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>AN ELEGY, &amp;c.</mainhead> <attbytes>18Kb</attbytes><volhead>An Elegy [1782]</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140163</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>AN ELEGY, &amp;c.</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>An Elegy [1782]</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000006</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000006</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AN ELEGY, &amp;c.</mainhead><volhead>An Elegy [1782]</volhead></atttitle><attsize>18Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1782</attpubn1><attpubn2>1782</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">Come</hi>, to my soul, O shade of Hosmer, come,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Tho' doubting senates ask thy aid in vain;</l>
<l ln="3        ">&indent;Attend the drooping virtues round thy tomb,</l>
<l ln="4        ">And hear a while the orphan'd Muse complain.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">&indent;The Muse which thy indulgence bade aspire,</l>
<l ln="6        ">And dare pursue thy distant steps to fame;</l>
<l ln="7        ">&indent;At thy command she first assum'd the lyre,</l>
<l ln="8        ">And hop'd a future laurel from thy name.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">&indent;How did thy smiles awake her infant song!</l>
<l ln="10      ">How did thy virtues animate the lay!</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;Still shall thy fate the dying strain prolong,</l>
<l ln="12      ">And bear her voice with thy lost form away.</l></stanza>
<pb n="6">
<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;Come to my soul thou venerable Sage,</l>
<l ln="14      ">In all the sheeted majesty of night,</l>
<l ln="15      ">&indent;Snatch the bold quill, control the noble rage,</l>
<l ln="16      ">And seize the raptur'd fancy in her flight.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">&indent;Come in the form that shadowy spirits dress,</l>
<l ln="18      ">When death's dim vail hath shrouded all their pride,</l>
<l ln="19      ">&indent;While yon tall cloud but emulates thy face,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Where the lone moonbeam trembles thro' its side.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">&indent;Come on the gale that listening midnight heaves,</l>
<l ln="22      ">When glare ey'd phantoms, bending with a bier,</l>
<l ln="23      ">&indent;Stalk thro' the mist, ascend the sounding graves,</l>
<l ln="24      ">And wake wild wonders in the startled ear.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">&indent;In this dread scene no more the wonted sires</l>
<l ln="26      ">Kindle my breast or ope a wish within,</l>
<l ln="27      ">&indent;The soul, distracted from herself retires,</l>
<l ln="28      ">And sighs to mingle and to soar with thine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">&indent;And where, thou blest immortal art thou flown?</l>
<l ln="30      ">Can these deep shades detain thy willing ear?</l>
<l ln="31      ">&indent;Canst thou from loaded breezes hear a groan?</l>
<l ln="32      ">Or stain thy spotless mantle with a tear?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">&indent;Can ought on earth thy flight hath left behind,</l>
<l ln="34      ">Borne in the music of a once lov'd strain,</l>
<l ln="35      ">&indent;Approach th'unbodied mansion of the mind?</l>
<l ln="36      ">Or bend one pitying look to earth again?</l></stanza>
<pb n="7">
<stanza><l ln="37      ">&indent;Can thence no thought to that fair seat descend?</l>
<l ln="38      ">The seat once joyous in thy joys below,</l>
<l ln="39      ">&indent;Where robes of fable sadness now depend,</l>
<l ln="40      ">And all the still solemnities of woe.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">&indent;Can the dear partner of thy tender years,</l>
<l ln="42      ">Sad as the misty fading face of even,</l>
<l ln="43      ">&indent;With all the wasted treasure of her tears,</l>
<l ln="44      ">Avert no smile nor bribe a care from heaven?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="45      ">&indent;While that young throng, that dear deserted train,</l>
<l ln="46      ">Where thy lov'd image soften'd sweetness wears,</l>
<l ln="47      ">&indent;Swell with new tenderness each following pain,</l>
<l ln="48      ">And add unnumber'd, undivided cares.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="49      ">&indent;Around the fair one see their beauties bloom,</l>
<l ln="50      ">(Or wilt thou not the moving fair one heed?)</l>
<l ln="51      ">&indent;How their keen anguish points the distant tomb,</l>
<l ln="52      ">Where all their joys and every hope is fled!</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="53      ">&indent;So lonely Cynthia, on her evening throne,</l>
<l ln="54      ">And all her young&hyphen;ey'd planetary train,</l>
<l ln="55      ">&indent;In languid lustre seek their sire the sun,</l>
<l ln="56      ">Down the still chambers of the western main.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="57      ">&indent;Yet that broad splendor from his nightly race,</l>
<l ln="58      ">With rising radiance shall the day restore;</l>
<l ln="59      ">&indent;Another spring renews fair nature's face,</l>
<l ln="60      ">And years and ages die to waken more.</l></stanza>
<pb n="8">
<stanza><l ln="61      ">&indent;But thou alas! no more on earth wilt tread,</l>
<l ln="62      ">Nor one short hour thy blest employments leave,</l>
<l ln="63      ">&indent;Tho' the sad knell, that hail'd thee to the dead,</l>
<l ln="64      ">Had doom'd thy helpless country to her grave.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="65      ">&indent;Thy country, whose still supplicating moan,</l>
<l ln="66      ">Implores thy counsels with an infant cry;</l>
<l ln="67      ">&indent;And loads the same stern Angel with a groan,</l>
<l ln="68      ">Which bore thy kindling spirit to the sky.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="69      ">&indent;Wilt thou (since nothing here could bribe thy stay,</l>
<l ln="70      ">And nothing here can tempt thee from on high,</l>
<l ln="71      ">&indent;Since tears of innocence must idly stray,</l>
<l ln="72      ">And grateful millions breathe the fruitless sigh;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="73      ">&indent;Since every tender tie that mortals prize,</l>
<l ln="74      ">And all that fame's immortal children gain,</l>
<l ln="75      ">&indent;Yield to th'untimely mandate of the skies,</l>
<l ln="76      ">And ask thy kind continuance still in vain;)</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="77      ">&indent;Wilt thou in seats of blessedness above,</l>
<l ln="78      ">Where cares of empire claim th'eternal ear,</l>
<l ln="79      ">&indent;Among thy country's guardian seraphs prove</l>
<l ln="80      ">The hand to cherish and the heart to hear?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="81      ">&indent;There while the dread sublimity of soul</l>
<l ln="82      ">O'er all the star&hyphen;eye'd heaven exalts thy throne,</l>
<l ln="83      ">&indent;While worlds beneath immeasurably roll,</l>
<l ln="84      ">And shew the well&hyphen;known circuit of thine own,</l></stanza>
<pb n="9">
<stanza><l ln="85      ">&indent;Wilt thou remark the bluely&hyphen;bending shore?</l>
<l ln="86      ">Where hills and champaigns stretch abroad their pride,</l>
<l ln="87      ">&indent;Where opening streams their lengthiest currents pour,</l>
<l ln="88      ">And heaps of heroes swell the crimson tide.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="89      ">&indent;Wilt thou recognize that confus'd uproar?</l>
<l ln="90      ">Towns curl'd in smoaky columns mounting high,</l>
<l ln="91      ">&indent;Mix'd with the clarion's desolating roar;</l>
<l ln="92      ">Rending and purpling all the nether sky.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="93      ">&indent;Amid the tumult, wilt thou see afar</l>
<l ln="94      ">Our laurel'd heroes striving for the day?</l>
<l ln="95      ">&indent;While clouds, unfolding, ope the wings of war,</l>
<l ln="96      ">Where the grim legions sweep the foes away.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="97      ">&indent;And while their deeds thy blest approvance claim,</l>
<l ln="98      ">While crouds of rival chiefs thy guidance share,</l>
<l ln="99      ">&indent;Behold that first, that finish'd heir of fame,</l>
<l ln="100    ">And be the best of heroes still thy care.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="101    ">&indent;That hero whose illuminating sword</l>
<l ln="102    ">Lights death and victory through the darken'd field,</l>
<l ln="103    ">&indent;Bids realms and ages waken at his word,</l>
<l ln="104    ">Their sire, their soul, their savior and their shield.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="105    ">&indent;Behold that Senate, whose delighted ear</l>
<l ln="106    ">With thy bold eloquence hath often rung,</l>
<l ln="107    ">&indent;Where trembling realms, for many a doubtful year,</l>
<l ln="108    ">Have learnt their sure salvation from thy tongue.</l></stanza>
<pb n="10">
<stanza><l ln="109    ">&indent;While cares of empires sit upon their brow,</l>
<l ln="110    ">And all th'increasing counsels of an age,</l>
<l ln="111    ">&indent;Demand, alike, bold virtue's warmest glow,</l>
<l ln="112    ">And the wide walks of science in the sage;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="113    ">&indent;Let thy own wisdom's ever beaming light</l>
<l ln="114    ">Illume their well&hyphen;known dignity of soul,</l>
<l ln="115    ">&indent;Let thy benevolence their hearts unite,</l>
<l ln="116    ">And every voice, and every wish control.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="117    ">&indent;Lift the deep curtain from the vale of time,</l>
<l ln="118    ">Where unborn years their future circles wind,</l>
<l ln="119    ">&indent;Where the broad interests of a growing clime</l>
<l ln="120    ">Spread to all realms and regulate mankind.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="121    ">&indent;Unfold to their keen penetrating view,</l>
<l ln="122    ">What to the infant empire should be known,</l>
<l ln="123    ">&indent;That worlds' and ages' happiness or woe,</l>
<l ln="124    ">Hang on th'important issue of their own.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="125    ">&indent;And sure thou wilt that honor'd realm revere,</l>
<l ln="126    ">Where first thine early steps began their fame,</l>
<l ln="127    ">&indent;Where thy lov'd memory, ever doubly dear,</l>
<l ln="128    ">Awakes a tenderer tribute to thy name.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="129    ">&indent;Canst thou forget, when youthful years began,</l>
<l ln="130    ">Where opening science kindled every grace,</l>
<l ln="131    ">&indent;And smil'd to see, ascending in the man,</l>
<l ln="132    ">The friend the pride the glory of his race?</l></stanza>
<pb n="11">
<stanza><l ln="133    ">&indent;Where civil rights, the dignity of men,</l>
<l ln="134    ">And all the extensive privilege of laws,</l>
<l ln="135    ">&indent;Roll'd from thy voice or brighten'd from thy pen,</l>
<l ln="136    ">Compel'd attention and secur'd applause.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="137    ">&indent;Where rising worth thine early name enroll'd</l>
<l ln="138    ">Among the first fam'd fathers of the age,</l>
<l ln="139    ">&indent;And bade the untarnish'd characters of gold</l>
<l ln="140    ">Flame in the front of glory's deathless page.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="141    ">&indent;Attentive still to virtue's noble aim,</l>
<l ln="142    ">And greatly stren'ous to advance her cause,</l>
<l ln="143    ">&indent;Lead thou her counsels animate her flame,</l>
<l ln="144    ">Sire of her sons, and guardian of her laws.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="145    ">&indent;And see! aloft in that sublime retreat,</l>
<l ln="146    ">Where injur'd rights obtain their last appeal,</l>
<l ln="147    ">&indent;How pensive justice o'er thy vacant seat,</l>
<l ln="148    ">With faltering hand suspends her turning scale.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="149    ">&indent;If chance some Hosmer, with an even eye,</l>
<l ln="150    ">And skill'd like thee to poize the trembling weight,</l>
<l ln="151    ">&indent;Should chear the nymph, thine honor'd place supply,</l>
<l ln="152    ">And bless the nations with a longer date;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="153    ">&indent;When from all bounds of this extensive land,</l>
<l ln="154    ">Or where wide oceans spread their coasts abroad,</l>
<l ln="155    ">&indent;Dark causes rise, demanding from his hand,</l>
<l ln="156    ">Th'impartial deep discernment of a god;</l></stanza>
<pb n="12">
<stanza><l ln="157    ">&indent;Then in his breast may all thy virtues rise,</l>
<l ln="158    ">And all thy dignity around him shine,</l>
<l ln="159    ">&indent;Then drop thy own blest mantle from the skies,</l>
<l ln="160    ">And make the person as the place divine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="161    ">&indent;He will, my friends&mdash;th'unbodied life above,</l>
<l ln="162    ">With every virtue brighten'd and refin'd,</l>
<l ln="163    ">&indent;That glow'd below, with patriotic love,</l>
<l ln="164    ">The love of happiness and human kind,</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="165    ">&indent;Will burn serener in a purer sky,</l>
<l ln="166    ">Where broader views and bolder thoughts unroll,</l>
<l ln="167    ">&indent;Where universal Being fills the eye,</l>
<l ln="168    ">And swells the unbounded wishes of the soul.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="169    ">&indent;No tender thought by heaven's own breath inspir'd,</l>
<l ln="170    ">Which taught the gentle bosom here to glow,</l>
<l ln="171    ">&indent;Which the warm breast with patriot ardor fir'd,</l>
<l ln="172    ">Or stole the secret tear for silent woe,</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="173    ">&indent;No tender thought by heaven's own will approv'd,</l>
<l ln="174    ">Can e'er forsake the mansion first assign'd;</l>
<l ln="175    ">&indent;But reaches still the object once belov'd,</l>
<l ln="176    ">And lives immortal in th'immortal mind.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="177    ">&indent;Fix'd in a brighter sphere, with surer aim,</l>
<l ln="178    ">Tho' greater scenes his growing views employ,</l>
<l ln="179    ">&indent;Yet Hosmer kindles with an Hosmer's flame,</l>
<l ln="180    ">And his dear country feeds his noblest joy.</l></stanza>
<pb n="13">
<stanza><l ln="181    ">&indent;He sees our rising, all&hyphen;involving cause,</l>
<l ln="182    ">Spread like the morn to every distant clime,</l>
<l ln="183    ">&indent;Awake the mild magnificence of laws,</l>
<l ln="184    ">And roll down blessings on the stream of time.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="185    ">&indent;Nor think, O hapless fair one, tho' awhile,</l>
<l ln="186    ">From thy fond arms his happier spirit rove,</l>
<l ln="187    ">&indent;That soaring innocence can cease to smile,</l>
<l ln="188    ">Or his Seraphic bosom cease to love.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="189    ">&indent;In Heaven's own breast the self&hyphen;existent fires,</l>
<l ln="190    ">E'er time began, illum'd th'eternal flame,</l>
<l ln="191    ">&indent;Lit from the beam, the Archangellic quires</l>
<l ln="192    ">Preserve th'unchanging ardor still the same.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="193    ">&indent;And shall the heaven&hyphen;born spirit after death,</l>
<l ln="194    ">Robb'd of its virtues from its nature fly?</l>
<l ln="195    ">&indent;Or lose in climes of bliss the aspiring breath,</l>
<l ln="196    ">Which wing'd its passage to its kindred sky?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="197    ">&indent;Think, in the chambers of eternal morn,</l>
<l ln="198    ">Where beauty blooms along the vernal vale,</l>
<l ln="199    ">&indent;Where loves and virtues every smile adorn,</l>
<l ln="200    ">And hymns of Angels swell the floating gale;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="201    ">&indent;Think how his well&hyphen;known sympathy of soul</l>
<l ln="202    ">Views every pain thy tenderness can know;</l>
<l ln="203    ">&indent;Counts the full tears in silence as they roll,</l>
<l ln="204    ">And learns the tale of every speaking woe.</l></stanza>
<pb n="14">
<stanza><l ln="205    ">&indent;Thou knowst, while here, he joy'd to give relief,</l>
<l ln="206    ">To call dark merit to the eye of day,</l>
<l ln="207    ">&indent;To rob the silent orphan of her grief,</l>
<l ln="208    ">And breathe the sigh from innocence away.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="209    ">&indent;How did the trembling visage of the poor,</l>
<l ln="210    ">With grateful glow embolden at his smile!</l>
<l ln="211    ">&indent;And learn, well pleas'd, within his wonted door,</l>
<l ln="212    ">Its joys to cherish, and its cares beguile.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="213    ">&indent;Thou knowst his early wish began to prize</l>
<l ln="214    ">The bliss that wayward mortals seldom find,</l>
<l ln="215    ">&indent;That lifts the frequent suppliant to the skies,</l>
<l ln="216    ">While answering blessings fill the raptur'd mind.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="217    ">&indent;Know then, fair mourner, from the climes of day,</l>
<l ln="218    ">(While these drear shades of solitude you tread)</l>
<l ln="219    ">&indent;His unseen hand companion of thy way,</l>
<l ln="220    ">Thro' the dark paths thy wandering steps shall lead.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="221    ">&indent;While all thy virtues rise before the throne,</l>
<l ln="222    ">And all thy griefs be number'd in his sight,</l>
<l ln="223    ">&indent;Those shall refine and ripen with his own,</l>
<l ln="224    ">And these be hush'd in everlasting night.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="225    ">&indent;Thy children too, his images below,</l>
<l ln="226    ">Fair as young plants, and smiling as the morn,</l>
<l ln="227    ">&indent;With thy own loveliness shall learn to glow,</l>
<l ln="228    ">And all thy graces brighten and adorn.</l></stanza>
<pb n="15">
<stanza><l ln="229    ">&indent;Short is the date that virtue from its home,</l>
<l ln="230    ">In these deep shades, can suffer and refine;</l>
<l ln="231    ">&indent;And when kind heaven relieves it from the doom,</l>
<l ln="232    ">Ours be the choice to tremble and resign.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="233    ">&indent;Vain were the task, the daring thought were vain,</l>
<l ln="234    ">To check the sun's bold circuit as he flies;</l>
<l ln="235    ">&indent;Nor think the cling of fondness can detain</l>
<l ln="236    ">The soaring seraph from his kindred skies.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="237    ">&indent;Then cease, fond partner of his earthly joys,</l>
<l ln="238    ">And leave behind each unavailing care;</l>
<l ln="239    ">&indent;Think what a scene his happier slight employs,</l>
<l ln="240    ">And haste to meet him and to mingle there.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
</div1></div0>
