<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140179</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>ON THE DISCOVERIES OF CAPTAIN LEWIS.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Cyclop&aelig;dia of American literature (1856)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140179</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>ON THE DISCOVERIES OF CAPTAIN LEWIS.</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Cyclop&aelig;dia of American literature (1856)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000013</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000013</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ON THE DISCOVERIES OF CAPTAIN LEWIS.</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Cyclop&aelig;dia of American literature (1856)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1856</attpubn1><attpubn2>1856</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Let the Nile cloak his head in the clouds, and defy</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The researches of science and time;</l>
<l ln="3        ">Let the Niger escape the keen traveller's eye,</l>
<l ln="4        ">&indent;By plunging or changing his clime.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Columbus! not so shall thy boundless domain</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;Defraud thy brave sons of their right:</l>
<l ln="7        ">Streams, midlands, and shorelands elude us in vain,</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;We shall drag their dark regions to light.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Look down, sainted sage, from thy synod of Gods;</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;See, inspired by thy venturous soul,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Mackenzie roll northward his earth&hyphen;draining floods,</l>
<l ln="12      ">&indent;And surge the broad waves to the pole.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">With the same soaring genius thy Lewis ascends,</l>
<l ln="14      ">&indent;And seizing the car of the sun,</l>
<l ln="15      ">O'er the sky&hyphen;propping hills and high waters he bends</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;And gives the proud earth a new zone.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Potowmak, Ohio, Missouri had felt</l>
<l ln="18      ">&indent;Half her globe in their cincture comprest;</l>
<l ln="19      ">His long curving course has completed the belt,</l>
<l ln="20      ">&indent;And tamed the last tide of the west.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">Then hear the loud voice of the nation proclaim,</l>
<l ln="22      ">&indent;And all ages resound the decree:</l>
<l ln="23      ">Let our occident stream bear the young hero's name</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;Who taught him his path to the sea.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">These four brother floods, like a garland of flowers,</l>
<l ln="26      ">&indent;Shall entwine all our states in a band,</l>
<l ln="27      ">Conform and confederate their wide spreading powers,</l>
<l ln="28      ">&indent;And their wealth and their wisdom expand.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">From Darien to Davis one garden shall bloom,</l>
<l ln="30      ">&indent;Where war's wearied banners are furl'd,</l>
<l ln="31      ">And the far scenting breezes that waft its perfume,</l>
<l ln="32      ">&indent;Shall settle the storms of the world.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">Then hear the loud voice of the nation proclaim</l>
<l ln="34      ">&indent;And all ages resound the decree:</l>
<l ln="35      ">Let our occident stream bear the young hero's name,</l>
<l ln="36      ">&indent;Who taught him his path to the sea.</l></stanza>
<pb n="397">
<stanza><l ln="37      ">&indent;&indent;Yon meteor&hyphen;mantled hill see Franklin tread.</l>
<l ln="38      ">Another line is, however, an improvement, the change from&mdash;</l>
<l ln="39      ">&indent;His daring toils, the threatening blast that wait,</l>
<l ln="40      ">To&mdash;</l>
<l ln="41      ">&indent;His well&hyphen;tried wires, that every tempest wait.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140180</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>ADVICE TO A RAVEN IN RUSSIA.</mainhead> <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Cyclop&aelig;dia of American literature (1856)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140180</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>ADVICE TO A RAVEN IN RUSSIA.</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Cyclop&aelig;dia of American literature (1856)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000014</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000014</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ADVICE TO A RAVEN IN RUSSIA.</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Cyclop&aelig;dia of American literature (1856)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>6Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1856</attpubn1><attpubn2>1856</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Black fool, why winter here? These frozen skies,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Worn by your wings and deafened by your cries,</l>
<pb n="398">
<l ln="3        ">Should warn you hence, where milder suns invite,</l>
<l ln="4        ">And Day alternates with his mother Night.</l>
<l ln="5        ">You fear, perhaps, your food will fail you there&mdash;</l>
<l ln="6        ">Your human carnage, that delicious fare,</l>
<l ln="7        ">That lured you hither, following still your friend,</l>
<l ln="8        ">The great Napoleon, to the world's bleak end.</l>
<l ln="9        ">You fear because the southern climes pour'd forth</l>
<l ln="10      ">Their clustering nations to infest the north&mdash;</l>
<l ln="11      ">Bavarians, Austrians&mdash;those who drink the Po,</l>
<l ln="12      ">And those who skirt the Tuscan seas below,</l>
<l ln="13      ">With all Germania, Neustria, Belgia, Gaul,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Doom'd here to wade through slaughter to their fall.</l>
<l ln="15      ">You fear he left behind no wars to feed</l>
<l ln="16      ">His feather'd cannibals and nurse the breed.</l>
<l ln="17      ">Fear not, my screamer, call your greedy train,</l>
<l ln="18      ">Sweep over Europe, hurry back to Spain&mdash;</l>
<l ln="19      ">You'll find his legions there, the valiant crew,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Please best their masters when they toil for you.</l>
<l ln="21      ">Abundant there they spread the country o'er,</l>
<l ln="22      ">And taint the breeze with every nation's gore&mdash;</l>
<l ln="23      ">Iberian, Russian, British, widely strown,</l>
<l ln="24      ">But still more wide and copious flows their own.</l>
<l ln="25      ">Go where you will, Calabria, Malta, Greece,</l>
<l ln="26      ">Egypt and Syria still his fame increase.</l>
<l ln="27      ">Domingo's fattened isle and India's plains</l>
<l ln="28      ">Glow deep with purple drawn from Gallic veins.</l>
<l ln="29      ">No raven's wing can stretch the flight so far</l>
<l ln="30      ">As the torn bandrols of Napoleon's war.</l>
<l ln="31      ">Choose then your climate, fix your best abode&mdash;</l>
<l ln="32      ">He'll make you deserts and he'll bring you blood.</l>
<l ln="33      ">How could you fear a dearth? Have not mankind,</l>
<l ln="34      ">Though slain by millions, millions left behind?</l>
<l ln="35      ">Has not conscription still the power to wield</l>
<l ln="36      ">Her annual falchion o'er the human field?</l>
<l ln="37      ">A faithful harvester! or if a man</l>
<l ln="38      ">Escape that gleaner, shall he 'scape the ban,</l>
<l ln="39      ">The triple ban, that, like the hound of hell,</l>
<l ln="40      ">Gripes with three joles to hold his victims well!</l>
<l ln="41      ">Fear nothing, then! hatch fast your ravenous brood,</l>
<l ln="42      ">Teach them to cry to Buonaparte for food.</l>
<l ln="43      ">They'll be, like you, of all his suppliant train,</l>
<l ln="44      ">The only class that never cries in vain!</l>
<l ln="45      ">For see what natural benefits you lend&mdash;</l>
<l ln="46      ">The surest way to fix the mutual friend&mdash;</l>
<l ln="47      ">While on his slaughtered troops your tribes are fed,</l>
<l ln="48      ">You cleanse his camp and carry off his dead,</l>
<l ln="49      ">Imperial scavenger, but now, you know,</l>
<l ln="50      ">Your work is vain amid these hills of snow.</l>
<l ln="51      ">His tentless troops are marbled through with frost,</l>
<l ln="52      ">And changed to crystal when the breath is lost.</l>
<l ln="53      ">Mere trunks of ice, though limn'd like human frames,</l>
<l ln="54      ">And lately warmed with life's endearing flames,</l>
<l ln="55      ">They cannot taint the air, the world infest,</l>
<l ln="56      ">Nor can you tear one fibre from their breast.</l>
<l ln="57      ">No! from their visual sockets as they lie,</l>
<l ln="58      ">With beak and claws you cannot pluck an eye&mdash;</l>
<l ln="59      ">The frozen orb, preserving still its form,</l>
<l ln="60      ">Defies your talons as it braves the storm,</l>
<l ln="61      ">But stands and stares to God as if to know,</l>
<l ln="62      ">In what curst hands he leaves his world below!</l>
<l ln="63      ">Fly then, or starve, though all the dreadful road</l>
<l ln="64      ">From Minsk to Moscow with their bodies strow'd</l>
<l ln="65      ">May count some myriads, yet they can't suffice</l>
<l ln="66      ">To feed you more beneath these dreadful skies.</l>
<l ln="67      ">Go back and winter in the wilds of Spain;</l>
<l ln="68      ">Feast there awhile, and in the next campaign</l>
<l ln="69      ">Rejoin your master, for you'll find him then,</l>
<l ln="70      ">With his new millions of the race of men,</l>
<l ln="71      ">Clothed in his thunders, all his flags unfurl'd,</l>
<l ln="72      ">Raging and storming o'er a prostrate world!</l>
<l ln="73      ">War after war his hungry soul requires;</l>
<l ln="74      ">State after state shall sink beneath his fires.</l>
<l ln="75      ">Yet other Spains in victim smoke shall rise.</l>
<l ln="76      ">And other Moscows suffocate the skies.</l>
<l ln="77      ">Each land lie reeking with its people slain,</l>
<l ln="78      ">And not a stream run bloodless to the main,</l>
<l ln="79      ">Till men resume their souls, and dare to shed</l>
<l ln="80      ">Earth's total vengeance on the monster's head!</l></poem>
</div2>
