<newatts><attidref>A2000016</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>To a Young Lady</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Go, Rose, my Chloe's bosom grace!</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;How happy should I prove,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Might I supply that envied place</l>
<l ln="4        ">&indent;With never fading love;</l>
<l ln="5        ">There, Ph&oelig;nix&hyphen;like, beneath her eye,</l>
<l ln="6        ">Involved in fragrance, burn and die.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">Know, hapless flower, that thou shalt find</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;More fragrant roses there;</l>
<l ln="9        ">I see thy withering head reclined</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;With envy and despair:</l>
<l ln="11      ">One common fate we both must prove&mdash;</l>
<l ln="12      ">You die with envy, I with love.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="29">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140185</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>[While scenes of transport every heart inspire]</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140185</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>[While scenes of transport every heart inspire]</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000017</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000017</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>[While scenes of transport every heart inspire]</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">While scenes of transport every heart inspire,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The Muse, too, triumphs in her kindling fire.</l>
<l ln="3        ">Blest in their bliss, she lifts a bolder wing,</l>
<l ln="4        ">Aids every wish and tunes the harp to sing;</l>
<l ln="5        ">To their glad concert wakes the accordant strain</l>
<l ln="6        ">And mingles with the music of the plain.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="7        ">&lsquo;Joy to the Bands,&rsquo; her voice arose,</l>
<l ln="8        ">&lsquo;Who chained that veteran host of foes;</l>
<l ln="9        ">Who bade Britannia's glory fade</l>
<l ln="10      ">And placed the wreath on fair Columbia's head.&rsquo;</l></pdiv>
<pb n="30">
<stage align="c">CHORUS.</stage>
<pdiv><l ln="11      ">&lsquo;Hail the day and mark it well:</l>
<l ln="12      ">Then the scourge of Freedom fell,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Then your dawning glory shone,&mdash;</l>
<l ln="14      ">Mark it, Freeman! 'tis your own.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="15      ">&lsquo;Now recount your toils with pleasure,</l>
<l ln="16      ">View the strife and sum the treasure;</l>
<l ln="17      ">Run the battles o'er again,</l>
<l ln="18      ">Sound the charge and sweep the plain;</l>
<l ln="19      ">Here behold the foe pursuing&mdash;</l>
<l ln="20      ">&indent;How he drives his headlong way,</l>
<l ln="21      ">Whelming towns and realms in ruin,</l>
<l ln="22      ">&indent;Sure to seize the distant prey.</l>
<l ln="23      ">False and faithless tribes adore him,</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;Join the shout and yield him room.</l>
<l ln="25      ">Now, Albania, fall before him&mdash;</l>
<l ln="26      ">&indent;Now, Rebellion, learn your doom.&rsquo;</l></pdiv>
<p ln="[27]">[The concluding stanza is as follows:]</p>
<pdiv><l ln="28      ">Then every glad blessing thy country can lend</l>
<l ln="29      ">&indent;When her foes and her slaughters shall cease,</l>
<l ln="30      ">Shall arise to the Hero who bade her ascend</l>
<l ln="31      ">&indent;To conquest, to glory, and peace.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="191">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140186</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>[Could youth, could innocence, could virtue save]</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140186</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>[Could youth, could innocence, could virtue save]</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000018</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000018</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>[Could youth, could innocence, could virtue save]</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Could youth, could innocence, could virtue save,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Our Charlotte sure had found a later grave.</l>
<l ln="3        ">But, hapless mother, cease: your tears but show</l>
<l ln="4        ">The poor scant measure of our common woe.</l>
<l ln="5        ">Ah! cease that vulgar grief: a tribute find</l>
<l ln="6        ">More just, more worthy her exalted mind.</l>
<l ln="7        ">Resume the virtues that you planted there,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Reclaim that merit none with you can share;</l>
<l ln="9        ">Reclaim her force of thought, her vermeil hue,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Your friends demand her promised life in you.</l></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="292">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140187</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>[Blest Hymen, hail that memorable day]</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140187</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>[Blest Hymen, hail that memorable day]</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000019</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000019</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>[Blest Hymen, hail that memorable day]</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Blest Hymen, hail that memorable day</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Whose twelfth return my constant bosom warms,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Whose morning rose with promised pleasure gay,</l>
<l ln="4        ">&indent;Whose faithful evening gave me Delia's charms&mdash;</l>
<l ln="5        ">Those charms that still, with ever new delight,</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;Assuage and feed the flames of young desire,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Whose magic powers can temper and unite</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;The husband's friendship with the lover's fire.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><stanza><l ln="9        ">Say, gentle god, if e'er thy torch before</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;Illum'ed the altar for so pure a pair?</l>
<l ln="11      ">If e'er approached thy consecrated bower</l>
<l ln="12      ">&indent;A swain so grateful, so divine a fair?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Love, the delusive Power who often flies</l>
<l ln="14      ">&indent;Submissive souls that yield to thy decree,</l>
<pb n="293">
<l ln="15      ">Charmed with our lasting flame, approves the ties,</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;Folds his white wings, and shares his throne with thee.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">United Sovereigns! hear my fervent prayer,</l>
<l ln="18      ">&indent;Extend through life your undivided sway,</l>
<l ln="19      ">In love and union bless your suppliant pair</l>
<l ln="20      ">&indent;With many a sweet return of this delightful day.</l></stanza></pdiv></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140188</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>[If nineteen years of marriage ties]</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140188</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>[If nineteen years of marriage ties]</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000020</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000020</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>[If nineteen years of marriage ties]</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">If nineteen years of marriage ties</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Can make me love so strong,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Pray tell how high the flame will rise</l>
<l ln="4        ">&indent;When nourished twice as long.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">For nourishment, like what you give,</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;So sweet, so wholesome too,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Will bid the torch forever live,</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;And live alone for you.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140189</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>[My foolish rhymes on wedding days]</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140189</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>[My foolish rhymes on wedding days]</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000021</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000021</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>[My foolish rhymes on wedding days]</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Epigram</attgenre></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">My foolish rhymes on wedding days</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;I thought would make you vain,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Or Love would sicken of his lays</l>
<l ln="4        ">&indent;And ask them back again.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">&ldquo;But little prospect now appears</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;That aught our souls can sever,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Since after Hymen's twenty years</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;I love you more than ever.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140190</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>[If seven long years of laboring life]</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140190</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>[If seven long years of laboring life]</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000022</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000022</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>[If seven long years of laboring life]</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">If seven long years of laboring life</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Old Jacob served to gain a wife,</l>
<l ln="3        ">She doubtless must have been the best,</l>
<l ln="4        ">The rarest beauty of the East&mdash;</l>
<l ln="5        ">For sure the sire of Jews had strove</l>
<l ln="6        ">To have his pennyworth even in love.</l>
<l ln="7        ">But thrice seven suns have passed the line</l>
<l ln="8        ">Since I have laboring been for mine,</l>
<l ln="9        ">And I'm expert at bargains too&mdash;</l>
<l ln="10      ">A Yankee blade, though not a Jew&mdash;</l>
<l ln="11      ">Which proves, unless I judge amiss,</l>
<l ln="12      ">My wife is thrice as good as his.</l>
<l ln="13      ">One thing I <hi r="italic">certainly</hi> can tell,</l>
<l ln="14      ">I always love her thrice as well.</l></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="294">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140191</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>[The ruffian of England with equal remorse]</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140191</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>[The ruffian of England with equal remorse]</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000023</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000023</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>[The ruffian of England with equal remorse]</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">The ruffian of England with equal remorse</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Cuts the head from his king and the tail from his horse;</l>
<l ln="3        ">The Frenchman, more polished, lets nature prevail,</l>
<l ln="4        ">Lets the king wear his head and the horse wear his tail.</l></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140192</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>[Ah, where's my dear Hubby, whom Fate, in its malice]</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140192</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>[Ah, where's my dear Hubby, whom Fate, in its malice]</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000024</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000024</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>[Ah, where's my dear Hubby, whom Fate, in its malice]</mainhead><volhead>[Poems, in] Life and Letters (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">Wife.</speaker>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&mdash;Ah, where's my dear Hubby, whom Fate, in its malice,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Snatched away long ago.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">Toot.&mdash;</speaker>
<l align="r" ln="3        ">Now, I'll bet he's at Calais.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">Wife.</speaker>
<l ln="4        ">&mdash;I'll bet he's not, though. But, Tooty, my dear,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Suppose him at Calais, when think he'll be here?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">Toot.</speaker>
<l ln="6        ">&mdash;Be here! let us count. This is Thursday you say,</l>
<l ln="7        ">His passport and baggage will take the whole day;</l>
<l ln="8        ">Then other vexations fall in by the hundred&mdash;</l>
<l ln="9        ">Surrounded, examined, palavered, and plundered.</l>
<l ln="10      ">But he'll set off to&hyphen;morrow, and then, I divine,</l>
<l ln="11      ">We shall have him next Sunday between us to dine;</l>
<l ln="12      ">For he'll whirl along rapidly through the relays,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Cheek by jowl with Machere, and in Parker's post&hyphen;chaise.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">Wife.</speaker>
<l ln="14      ">&mdash;All that's but a fancy. I'll bet what you dare</l>
<l ln="15      ">He's not here on Sunday, nor is he now there.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">Toot.</speaker>
<l ln="16      ">&mdash;I'll hold you ten guineas, and sixpence to boot.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">Wife.</speaker>
<l ln="17      ">&mdash;Done.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">Toot.&mdash;</speaker>
<l align="c" ln="18      ">Done, here's my hand for't.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">Hub.&mdash;</speaker>
<l align="r" ln="19      ">I'll go halves with Toot.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>
</div1></div0>
