HYMNS AND <hi r="smcap">Spiritual Songs</hi>. <attbytes>24Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z100140212</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd1>
<pb>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140213</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead><hi r="smcap">Hymn</hi> LXIII. <hi r="italic">Our Saviour present at his Table</hi>.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140213</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>Hymn LXIII. Our Saviour present at his Table.</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000040</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000040</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>Hymn LXIII. Our Saviour present at his Table.</mainhead><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1785</attpubn1><attpubn2>1785</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Metrical Psalm</attgenre></newatts>
<stanza><caption>1</caption>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Come</hi> let us join the sacred song</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To our ascended Lord;</l>
<l ln="3        ">Ye saints and angels round his throne,</l>
<l ln="4        ">&indent;And we around his board.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>2</caption>
<l ln="5        ">Tho' rais'd beyond the worlds of light,</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;His brighter glories shine,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Where purer souls enjoy the sight</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;And presence more divine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>3</caption>
<l ln="9        ">Yet here, unseen by mortal eyes,</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;The boundless God resides,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Renews the atoning sacrifice</l>
<l ln="12      ">&indent;And o'er the feast presides.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>4</caption>
<l ln="13      ">Let every hand that shares the food</l>
<l ln="14      ">&indent;And every heart with fear,</l>
<l ln="15      ">Feel the full presence of the God,</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;That spreads his bounties here:</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>5</caption>
<l ln="17      ">But Oh, the love, the wondrous love</l>
<l ln="18      ">&indent;The bleeding Lord displays,</l>
<l ln="19      ">Shall earth's united songs improve,</l>
<l ln="20      ">&indent;And heaven's eternal praise.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140214</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead><hi r="smcap">Hymn</hi> LXV. <hi r="italic">Innumerable mercies acknowledged</hi>.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140214</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>Hymn LXV. Innumerable mercies acknowledged.</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000041</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000041</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>Hymn LXV. Innumerable mercies acknowledged.</mainhead><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1785</attpubn1><attpubn2>1785</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Metrical Psalm</attgenre></newatts>
<stanza><caption>1</caption>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">In</hi> glad amazement, Lord, I stand,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Amidst the bounties of thy hand;</l>
<l ln="3        ">How numberless those bounties are!</l>
<l ln="4        ">How rich, how various and how fair!</l></stanza>
<pb>
<stanza><caption>2</caption>
<l ln="5        ">But oh, what poor returns I bring!</l>
<l ln="6        ">What lifeless songs of praise I sing!</l>
<l ln="7        ">Lord, I confess, with humble shame,</l>
<l ln="8        ">My offerings scarce deserve the name.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>3</caption>
<l ln="9        ">Fain would my labouring heart devise</l>
<l ln="10      ">Some nobler gift and sacrifice;</l>
<l ln="11      ">It sinks beneath the mighty load</l>
<l ln="12      ">That I should render to my God.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>4</caption>
<l ln="13      ">To him I consecrate my praise,</l>
<l ln="14      ">And vow the remnant of my days;</l>
<l ln="15      ">Enlarge my soul with grace divine,</l>
<l ln="16      ">And make it worthier to be thine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>5</caption>
<l ln="17      ">Give me at length an angel's tongue,</l>
<l ln="18      ">To sound thro' heaven the grateful song;</l>
<l ln="19      ">A theme so great, my voice shall raise,</l>
<l ln="20      ">And crown eternity with praise.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140215</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead><hi r="smcap">Hymn</hi> LXVI. <hi r="italic">For a vacant Congregation</hi>.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140215</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>Hymn LXVI. For a vacant Congregation.</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000042</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000042</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>Hymn LXVI. For a vacant Congregation.</mainhead><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1785</attpubn1><attpubn2>1785</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Metrical Psalm</attgenre></newatts>
<stanza><caption>1</caption>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">O God</hi> of heaven, whose gentle ray,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Illumes the worlds of light,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Thy wisdom rules the realms of day,</l>
<l ln="4        ">&indent;And leads the host of night.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>2</caption>
<l ln="5        ">Behold thy waiting servants stand,</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;And claim with feeble cries,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Some skilful guide with gentle hand</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;To lead us to the skies.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>3</caption>
<l ln="9        ">While absent from thy temple, Lord</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;Like wandering flocks we stray</l>
<l ln="11      ">We lose the memory of thy word</l>
<l ln="12      ">&indent;And waste the sacred day.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>4</caption>
<l ln="13      ">And when, within these walls of thine</l>
<l ln="14      ">&indent;We find our wonted place;</l>
<l ln="15      ">How faint our feeble voices join</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;To seek thy pardoning grace.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>5</caption>
<l ln="17      ">Almighty Saviour, hear our prayer,</l>
<l ln="18      ">&indent;Some chosen servant raise,</l>
<pb>
<l ln="19      ">For us the bread of life to share</l>
<l ln="20      ">&indent;And help our lips to praise.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>6</caption>
<l ln="21      ">Then in thy house, with joy unknown</l>
<l ln="22      ">&indent;We'll raise a nobler song,</l>
<l ln="23      ">Till we shall meet around thy throne,</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;And join the heavenly throng.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140216</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead><hi r="smcap">Hymn</hi> LXVII. <hi r="italic">For a New&hyphen;Year's Day</hi>.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140216</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>Hymn LXVII. For a New&hyphen;Year's Day.</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000043</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000043</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>Hymn LXVII. For a New&hyphen;Year's Day.</mainhead><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1785</attpubn1><attpubn2>1785</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Metrical Psalm</attgenre></newatts>
<stanza><caption>1</caption>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Eternal</hi> Source of every joy,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Thy praise shall every voice employ,</l>
<l ln="3        ">While we within thy courts appear,</l>
<l ln="4        ">And sing the bounties of the year.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>2</caption>
<l ln="5        ">As worlds of glory round thee roll,</l>
<l ln="6        ">Thy hand supports the stedfast pole,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Directs the sun what hour to rise,</l>
<l ln="8        ">And darkness when to veil the skies.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>3</caption>
<l ln="9        ">The flowery Spring at thy command</l>
<l ln="10      ">Embalms the air, and paints the land;</l>
<l ln="11      ">The blazing beams of Summer shine</l>
<l ln="12      ">To raise the corn and cheer the vine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>4</caption>
<l ln="13      ">Thy hand in Autumn richly pours</l>
<l ln="14      ">The copious fruits along the shores,</l>
<l ln="15      ">While wintry storms direct our eyes</l>
<l ln="16      ">With fear and wonder to the skies.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>5</caption>
<l ln="17      ">Seasons, and months, and weeks, and days</l>
<l ln="18      ">Demand returning songs of praise;</l>
<l ln="19      ">The opening light and evening shade</l>
<l ln="20      ">Shall see the cheerful homage paid.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>6</caption>
<l ln="21      ">And Oh, may our harmonious tongues</l>
<l ln="22      ">In worlds unknown pursue the songs;</l>
<l ln="23      ">And in those brighter courts adore,</l>
<l ln="24      ">Where days and years revolve no more.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200140217</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead><hi r="smcap">Hymn</hi> LXVIII. <hi r="italic">A Hymn for Marriage</hi>.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200140217</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>Hymn LXVIII. A Hymn for Marriage.</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A2000044</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A2000044</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>Hymn LXVIII. A Hymn for Marriage.</mainhead><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1785</attpubn1><attpubn2>1785</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Metrical Psalm</attgenre></newatts>
<stanza><caption>1</caption>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Great</hi> God, who form'd for social joys</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Our natures by thy power and grace,</l>
<l ln="3        ">And join'd in blest connubial ties,</l>
<l ln="4        ">&indent;The parents of our favour'd race.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>2</caption>
<l ln="5        ">Our Saviour, our ascended Lord,</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;In Cana once a heavenly guest,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Whose bounty cheer'd the friendly board</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;Whose presence grac'd the nuptial feast.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>3</caption>
<l ln="9        ">Attend with smiles of heavenly love,</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;The pair thy sacred laws combine;</l>
<l ln="11      ">Their union bless, their vows approve,</l>
<l ln="12      ">&indent;And crown the rites with grace divine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>4</caption>
<l ln="13      ">Let love assist their mutual toils,</l>
<l ln="14      ">&indent;And every social bliss bestow;</l>
<l ln="15      ">Increase each joy with friendly smiles,</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;And share and soften every woo.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>5</caption>
<l ln="17      ">While each a kindly aid imparts,</l>
<l ln="18      ">&indent;To run secure the heavenly race;</l>
<l ln="19      ">And make their dwelling and their hearts,</l>
<l ln="20      ">&indent;Perpetual temples of thy praise.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>6</caption>
<l ln="21      ">When death dissolves these sacred ties,</l>
<l ln="22      ">&indent;May each to happier realms remove;</l>
<l ln="23      ">There meet and range the peaceful skies,</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;In bands of everlasting love.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<caption r="smcap">The End.</caption>
<div2><comhd2><idref>Z200140218</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

MEDITATIOMS ON DEATH AND THE GRAVE <attbytes>15Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200140218</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>
<pb n="2">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300140219</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812<sombiog>214</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>Meditations on DEATH and the GRAVE.</mainhead> <attbytes>10Kb</attbytes><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300140219</ID><A1>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</A1><T1>Meditations on DEATH and the GRAVE.</T1><PBL>Published by Joseph Milligan</PBL><Y1>1825</Y1><T2>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Barlow, Joel, 1754-1812</attpoet><attidref>A3000045</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>A3000045</attidref><attdbase>American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>Meditations on DEATH and the GRAVE.</mainhead><volhead>A translation of Sundry Psalms (1785)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>10Kb</attsize><attperi>Later Eighteenth-Century 1750-1799</attperi><attpubn1>1785</attpubn1><attpubn2>1785</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>214</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Metrical Psalm</attgenre></newatts>
<stanza><caption>1</caption>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I crave</hi> your calm attention now</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Till I reveal my Mind to you,</l>
<l ln="3        ">And tell you where my Thoughts were led</l>
<l ln="4        ">Out in the Tombs among the dead.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>2</caption>
<l ln="5        ">'Twas when the Care of Life had fled</l>
<l ln="6        ">And Night's dark curtain spread his shade,</l>
<l ln="7        ">And sweet Repose had clos'd mine Eyes</l>
<l ln="8        ">I heard a voice that bid me rise&mdash;</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>3</caption>
<l ln="9        ">Arise, go view your other Bed</l>
<l ln="10      ">That death is making with the dead:</l>
<l ln="11      ">Another dwelling you must have,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Though little thought on, 'tis the Grave.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>4</caption>
<l ln="13      ">O solemn, solemn was the Time</l>
<l ln="14      ">When first this Messenger came in,</l>
<l ln="15      ">For to invite me for to come</l>
<l ln="16      ">And view my lodging in the Tomb.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>5</caption>
<l ln="17      ">What frightful Apprehensions run</l>
<l ln="18      ">In trickling Streams through ev'ry Vein.</l>
<l ln="19      ">Dare not refuse, dare not obey&mdash;</l>
<l ln="20      ">Beneath these frightful Thoughts I lay.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>6</caption>
<l ln="21      ">And here I shrunk, I darn't comply,</l>
<l ln="22      ">But yet he did repeat this cry:</l>
<l ln="23      ">I yielded then to go and head</l>
<l ln="24      ">The gloomy Mansions of the dead.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>7</caption>
<l ln="25      ">Then I arose at his command</l>
<l ln="26      ">And went to view the solemn Land</l>
<pb n="3">
<l ln="27      ">While thoughts most frightfully did roll,</l>
<l ln="28      ">That overwhelm'd my fainting Soul.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>8</caption>
<l ln="29      ">So great, so solemn was the thought</l>
<l ln="30      ">To think how soon I must be brought</l>
<l ln="31      ">To view Death's gloomy dark abode,</l>
<l ln="32      ">I fell beneath the heavy load.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>9</caption>
<l ln="33      ">But soon a Voice to me was said,</l>
<l ln="34      ">Arise, arise, be not afraid;</l>
<l ln="35      ">Why do you fear to go and view</l>
<l ln="36      ">This lodging soon will be for you,</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>10</caption>
<l ln="37      ">Then I received strength and pow'r</l>
<l ln="38      ">Sufficient for that very Hour.</l>
<l ln="39      ">Then walking onwards to the Gate,</l>
<l ln="40      ">That leads unto this solemn Place.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>11</caption>
<l ln="41      ">How slow, how solemn did the Door</l>
<l ln="42      ">Move back for me to enter there,</l>
<l ln="43      ">Till I had pass'd, there it remain'd,</l>
<l ln="44      ">Then slowly moved back again.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>12</caption>
<l ln="45      ">Soon as we got within the Wall</l>
<l ln="46      ">My guide gave me another call,</l>
<l ln="47      ">Saying, come see the seat of sin,</l>
<l ln="48      ">Walk round and see what it has done.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>13</caption>
<l ln="49      ">Then I went forth at his command,</l>
<l ln="50      ">Walk'd round and viewed that solemn land,</l>
<l ln="51      ">There I beheld the fatal Wound,</l>
<l ln="52      ">Lie mouldering there beneath the Ground.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>14</caption>
<l ln="53      ">My thoughts soon back to Adam run</l>
<l ln="54      ">And cried out, what have you done?</l>
<l ln="55      ">Is this the dreadful Wound you gave,</l>
<l ln="56      ">A Wound that sinks down to the Grave.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>15</caption>
<l ln="57      ">But I another wonder found</l>
<l ln="58      ">To view the solemn Court around.</l>
<l ln="59      ">All bound in Bands of Vanity,</l>
<l ln="60      ">In perfect peace and Harmony.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>16</caption>
<l ln="61      ">How strangely did this sight appear</l>
<l ln="62      ">To see the great and small lie here?</l>
<pb n="4">
<l ln="63      ">The rich, the poor, the bond and free</l>
<l ln="64      ">In band of Harmony agree.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>17</caption>
<l ln="65      ">There lay the gallant and the brave</l>
<l ln="66      ">Both mouldering in the silent Grave.</l>
<l ln="67      ">The Fool, the Beggar fill'd a seat</l>
<l ln="68      ">As high as any in this Court.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>18</caption>
<l ln="69      ">There mighty Kings and Princes lay</l>
<l ln="70      ">Chain'd down in silence in the Clay.</l>
<l ln="71      ">There Counsellors and Judges cease</l>
<l ln="72      ">To grant Advice or give release.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>19</caption>
<l ln="73      ">There I beheld the highest trust,</l>
<l ln="74      ">Pull'd down, lay level'd with the Dust,</l>
<l ln="75      ">The great, the mighty and the proud,</l>
<l ln="76      ">They all lay equal'd in the croud.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>20</caption>
<l ln="77      ">Sworn Enemies there I beheld</l>
<l ln="78      ">Had laid aside both sword and shield,</l>
<l ln="79      ">The Hand forever had forgot</l>
<l ln="80      ">To draw the spear, or heave a shot.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>21</caption>
<l ln="81      ">The slandrous and backsliding Tongue</l>
<l ln="82      ">Lay bound in silence in the Tomb:</l>
<l ln="83      ">the furious Temper's cease to rage</l>
<l ln="84      ">And lay in Death's cold gloomy shades.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>22</caption>
<l ln="85      ">The bold Plasphemer's Tongue lay bound</l>
<l ln="86      ">With chains of silence in the ground:</l>
<l ln="87      ">His Oaths that once defil'd the Air</l>
<l ln="88      ">Lay bound in Death's cold Prison there.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>23</caption>
<l ln="89      ">I saw the vigorous boldest Face</l>
<l ln="90      ">Lay mouldering in this solemn Place;</l>
<l ln="91      ">The active Limbs lost all ther Power</l>
<l ln="92      ">In Death's decisive solemn Hour.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>24</caption>
<l ln="93      ">There I beheld and lo I found</l>
<l ln="94      ">A lovely youth lye in the Ground:</l>
<l ln="95      ">'Twas but a little while before</l>
<l ln="96      ">I saw him flourish like a Flower.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>25</caption>
<l ln="97      ">But O the shaft of Death was flung</l>
<l ln="98      ">And cut the tender Flower down.</l>
<pb n="5">
<l ln="99      ">Death's sharpen'd Arrows gave the wound,</l>
<l ln="100    ">And now he moulders in the Ground.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>26</caption>
<l ln="101    ">The lovely Flesh, the sparkling Eyes</l>
<l ln="102    ">Lay mouldering in Eternity;</l>
<l ln="103    ">The blooming Cheek that once was worn</l>
<l ln="104    ">Is now a Feast for odious Worms.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>27</caption>
<l ln="105    ">The lovely Frame the active Hands</l>
<l ln="106    ">Lay bound in Death's cold Prison Bands.</l>
<l ln="107    ">The burning Flesh, the harmless Tongue</l>
<l ln="108    ">Lay mouldering in the silent Tomb.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>28</caption>
<l ln="109    ">The tender Skin, the curious Frame,</l>
<l ln="110    ">The blooming Countenance was gone,</l>
<l ln="111    ">The softest Flesh, the lovely Charms</l>
<l ln="112    ">Lay clasp'd in Death's cold icy arms.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>29</caption>
<l ln="113    ">But here my thoughts they took a wing,</l>
<l ln="114    ">Flew back and view'd the Race of Man,</l>
<l ln="115    ">And lo I found the num'rous Throng</l>
<l ln="116    ">Lay down in Death's cold shady Tomb.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>30</caption>
<l ln="117    ">Alas! the Ruins here I found</l>
<l ln="118    ">Of all Mankind, lay in the Ground;</l>
<l ln="119    ">From Adam down unto this Day.</l>
<l ln="120    ">They all lay mouldering in Clay.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>31</caption>
<l ln="121    ">What Millions! Millions! had been slain</l>
<l ln="122    ">By Death, that conquering, mighty King?</l>
<l ln="123    ">What crowds of num'rous corps I found</l>
<l ln="124    ">Lay cold and mouldering in the Ground.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>32</caption>
<l ln="125    ">Here was a melancholly Land;</l>
<l ln="126    ">And Death, the King of Terrors reign'd,</l>
<l ln="127    ">His mighty Hand his Sword he hurl'd,</l>
<l ln="128    ">Made Inroads through the lower World.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>33</caption>
<l ln="129    ">But ah how frail this num'rous crowd?</l>
<l ln="130    ">I view'd grim Death not satisfy'd</l>
<l ln="131    ">Although he'd struck from Shore to Shore,</l>
<l ln="132    ">The hungry Grave still cried <hi r="italic">more</hi>.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>34</caption>
<l ln="133    ">No nor enough he ne'er will have</l>
<l ln="134    ">Till he has crouded in the Grave;</l>
<pb n="6">
<l ln="135    ">His Mouth will never be confin'd</l>
<l ln="136    ">Till he's devour'd all human Kind.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>35</caption>
<l ln="137    ">This faint Idea mine Eyes have seen</l>
<l ln="138    ">Of things that's over, past and gone&mdash;</l>
<l ln="139    ">And now upon another Theme</l>
<l ln="140    ">Of things that's present, and to come.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>
<div3>
<poem>
